708975f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 53rd Street (West)
708975f-a.text:
Fifth Ave., west side, north from West 53rd to 54th Streets. Shown
at the N.W. corner of 53rd Street is St. Thomas Protestant Episcopal
Church, organized in 1823 when its first church was at Broadway and
Houston Street; then a rural suburb. The parish attained te a high
degree of prosperity under the rectorship of Dr. Francis L. Hawks, but
as early as 1843 the need of a location farther up-town began to be felt,
and in 1870 the present edifice was opened for worship which was altered
in 1911 to appear as shown.
1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Writers Project.

708986f.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 53rd Street (West)
708986f.text:
(1)
Fifth Ave., (left) west side, south from and including West 54th to
West 53rd Streets, showing two private residences bearing Nos. 684 and
680, and St. Thomas Church (P.E.). No. 680 (adjoining the church) is the
residence of Dr. W. Seward Webb. The two residences were demolished and
on their site now (1937) stands a 6-story building occupied by fashionable
ladies' apparel shops.
Prior to 1908.
